Tariff Volume No. 1 Wildflower Solar LLC Wholesale Marked-Based Rate Tariff Providing for Sales of Capacity, Energy, or Ancillary Services Tariff Volume No. 1
1. Availability. Wildflower Solar LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser, the ancillary services listed below:
a. RTO/ISO Specific PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve), for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. b. Third Party Provider Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity and ancillary services by Seller which are subject to the jurisdiction of this Commission.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority.
In Wildflower Solar LLC, Docket No. ER23- (2023), the Commission granted Seller the following:
a. Exemptions: (a) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations requiring the filing of cost-of-service information, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (b) waiver of Part 41 and Part 101, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. ?? 141.14 and 141.15; (c) waiver of Part 141 of the Commission's regulations concerning accounting and reporting requirements; and (d) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumption of liabilities.
b. Limitations: Seller does not have authority under this tariff to make sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area, the Progress Energy Carolinas balancing authority areas, or in the following balancing authority areas in Florida: City of New Smyrna Beach and Duke Energy Florida (the "Mitigated Markets"). See Duke Power, a Div. of Duke Energy Corp., 111 FERC ? 61,506, at P 61 (2005) (limitation on market-based rate sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area); Florida Power Corp., 113 FERC ? 61,131, at P 17 (2005) (limitations on market-based rate sales within the Progress Energy Carolinas balancing authority areas and Peninsular Florida); see also Duke Energy Corp., 136 FERC ? 61,245 (2011); Duke Energy Corp., 139 FERC ? 61,194 (2012); and Duke Energy Florida, LLC 179 ? 61,141 (2022). Any sales by Seller within the Mitigated Markets will be made in accordance with the rate schedules approved by the Commission prior to Seller commencing such sales.
7. Modifications. Seller may unilaterally apply, under Federal Power Act section 205 and the regulations promulgated thereunder, to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Tariff.
8. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a), in the MISO region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a), in the Northeast, Southwest, Southwest Power Pool, Southeast, and Northwest regions.

SHARED FACILITIES AND CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT This SHARED FACILITIES AND CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this "Agreement"), dated as of September 8, 2022 (the "Effective Date"), is entered into by and among WILDFLOWER SOLAR LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("WFS"), WILDFLOWER SOLAR 2 LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("WFS2"), WILDFLOWER SOLAR 3 LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("WFS3"), and DUKE ENERGY RENEWABLE SERVICES, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Manager"). WFS, WFS2, WFS3 and Manager are sometimes each referred to separately in this Agreement as a "Party" or collectively as the "Parties". Capitalized terms used herein and not otherwise defined shall have the meaning ascribed to them in Section 1.1. RECITALS A. WFS is developing certain solar power generating and related facilities to be located in DeSoto County, Mississippi, with a net nameplate generating capacity of up to 100 megawatts (MW)(AC) measured at the Point of Interconnection (the "WFS Project"). B. WFS2 is developing certain solar power generating and related facilities to be located in DeSoto County, Mississippi, with a net nameplate generating capacity of up to 100 MW(AC) measured at the Point of Interconnection (the "WFS2 Project"). C. WFS3 is developing certain solar, battery storage and related facilities to be located in DeSoto County, Mississippi, with a net nameplate generating capacity of up to 250 megawatts MW(AC) measured at the Point of Interconnection (the "WFS3 Project"). D. In connection with the development and operation of the Projects, (i) WFS will design, engineer and construct the Shared Facilities in accordance with the Interconnection Agreements, this Agreement and the Approved Plans, and (ii) WFS, WFS2 and WFS3 and their permitted successors and assigns will jointly own and share the use of the Shared Facilities subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. E. The Co-Tenants also wish to contract with the Manager for the provision of the services set forth herein with respect to the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area, and the Manager wishes to accept said engagement, subject to the terms and conditions contained herein.
AGREEMENT NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual agreements set forth herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS 1.1 Certain Definitions. As used in this Agreement, the following capitalized terms shall have the meanings set forth below: "Additional Project Real Estate Agreements" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.5(f). "Additional Shared Facilities Area" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.5(e). "Affiliate" means with respect to any Person, each Person that directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with, such Person. The terms "control", "under common control with" and correlative terms include the possession, directly or indirectly, of the authority to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities, by contract or otherwise. "Annual Shared Facilities Budget" has the meaning set forth in Section 4.1(a). "Automobile Liability" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1(d). "Business Day" means a day other than Saturday, Sunday or a day on which banks are authorized to be closed for business in the State of Mississippi. "Casualty Event" means an event that causes all or a portion of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area to be damaged, destroyed or rendered unfit for normal use for any reason whatsoever. "CGL" has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1(d). "Clearway Facilities Percentage Interest" means for WFS2 and WFS3, the percentage equal to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity divided by the total Maximum Capacity of both WSF2 and WFS3. "Code" means the Internal Revenue Code of 1986. "Condemnation Event" means any compulsory transfer or taking or transfer under threat of compulsory transfer or taking of all or a material part of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area by any Governmental Authority or entity acting under power of eminent domain. "Confidential Information" means the terms and provisions of this Agreement and, with respect to a given Disclosing Party and the respective Receiving Party, collectively and individually, all data (including any Project operating and performance data), materials and information (including software, data, technology, know-how, trade secrets, processes, ideas, inventions (whether patentable or not), prototypes, schematics, design plans, drawings, pricing information, customer and service provider lists, business arrangements, business information, financial information, financial results, technical information, analyses, forecasts, compilations, studies, contracts, agreements, and planning or strategy information) provided by or on behalf of a Party (each Party in such capacity, a "Disclosing Party") to any other Party (each Party in such capacity, a "Receiving Party") or the Receiving Party's Representatives, or to which the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party's Representatives are given access by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party, in written or electronic form, related to the Disclosing Party, the Disclosing Party's Project, the Shared Facilities, the Shared Facilities Area in connection with this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Confidential Information under this Agreement does not include any information that: (a) is now publicly available, or that later becomes publicly available through no action by the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party's Representatives in violation of this Agreement; (b) is already in the possession of the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party's Representatives and is not, to Receiving Party's knowledge, subject to a confidentiality or fiduciary obligation at the time of the information's disclosure under this Agreement; (c) is lawfully received from any source other than the Disclosing Party or the Disclosing Party's Representatives under circumstances not involving, to the Receiving Party's knowledge, a breach of any fiduciary or confidentiality obligation; or (d) is independently developed by or for the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party's Representatives without reference to, or the use of, any portion of the Confidential Information; provided that all information related to (i) WFS's Project shall be deemed after the Effective Date for all purposes of this definition to be Confidential Information of such Project, developed solely by such Project, and unknown to WFS2, WFS3 or their Representatives and (ii) the WFS2 and WFS3 Project shall be deemed after the Effective Date for all purposes of this definition to be Confidential Information of such Project, developed solely by such Project, and unknown to the WFS or its Representatives. "Co-Tenant" or "Co-Tenants" means, individually or collectively, as applicable, WFS WFS2 and WFS3, and their permitted successors and assigns under this Agreement during the time each such party holds a Percentage Interest in the Shared Facilities; provided that such Party has not ceased to be a Co-Tenant in accordance with this Agreement. "Consultation Period" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.1(a). "Disclosing Party" has the meaning set forth in the definition of "Confidential Information". "Dispute" means any dispute, controversy or claim between the Parties arising out of or relating to this Agreement or the breach, termination or validity hereof, including, without limitation, any aspects of any proposed Annual Shared Facilities Budget and/or Maintenance Services Agreement. "Effective Date" has the meaning set forth in the preamble. "Election Notice" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.2(a). "Election Notice Co-Tenant" has the meaning set forth in Section 4.1(a). "Entergy" means Entergy Mississippi, LLC, a Texas limited liability company. "Emergency" means (a) any occurrence with respect to the Shared Facilities, Shared Facilities Area or the Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area that, in the reasonable judgment of Manager or a Co-Tenant (as the case may be), requires immediate action in order to prevent or mitigate serious actual or potential hazard to the safety of Persons or damage to property, or to prevent termination of a Co-Tenant's Power Purchase Agreement or Interconnection Agreement, or a material violation of any Applicable Law or Governmental Approval or any directive by a Governmental Authority or Transmission Provider and/or (b) a System Emergency. "EWG" means an "exempt wholesale generator," as such term is defined in Section 1262(6) of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005 and the FERC's regulations at 18 C.F.R. ?? 366.1 and 366.7 (2016). "Federal Power Act" means the Federal Power Act, 16, USC Chapter 12 ,as amended from time to time. "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. "Interconnection Provider" means MISO, the Transmission Owner, or any other Person providing interconnection services with respect to the Shared Facilities or for the benefit of one or more Projects. "Lost Production Damages" means the total payment lost for products (including energy, green attributes, capacity or other products) sold or hedged under the relevant Power Purchase Agreement, or through the MISO markets or other organized market for such products, that are not generated and/or delivered, any resource adequacy or availability incentive or bonus payments lost, and any resource adequacy deficit payment charges, minimum energy delivery obligation charges, costs to obtain required replacement products for those products that are not generated and delivered, or other penalties, costs or charges incurred, by an Co-Tenant under any Power Purchase Agreement, Transmission Provider's open access transmission tariff or otherwise, as a direct result of any interruptions or curtailments of output from its Project. "Maintenance Services Agreement" means any maintenance services subcontract executed by the Manager and an operator selected by the Manager, setting forth a scope of work for maintaining, inspecting and repairing the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area in accordance with the Annual Shared Facilities Budget then in effect. "Major Decision(s)" means: (a) any sale, lease or other voluntary disposition of all or any material portion of the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Area, other than in connection with a Transfer or collateral assignment in accordance with the requirements of Article 7; (b) any encumbrance or grant of any Lien on the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, other than Permitted Liens; (c) any action that would materially change or impact the regulatory status or scheduling capacity of any Co-Tenant (other than an action taken by a Co-Tenant solely with respect to the scheduling capacity or regulatory status of the Co-Tenant taking such action) or the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area; (d) any capital expenditures that are in excess of one hundred and ten percent (110%) of the aggregate amount budgeted in Annual Shared Facilities Budget, except in an Emergency; (e) any modification, amendment or change to, or waiver of any provision of, this Agreement; or (f) any action that could reasonably be expected to materially and adversely impact any Co-Tenant's ability to use the Shared Facilities, the Shared Facilities Area, and its Interconnection Agreement to interconnect its Project up to its Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection other than such temporary curtailments or disconnections that are expressly authorized hereunder. "NERC" means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation, or any successor thereto, and any regional entity to which NERC delegates its authority as the Electric Reliability Organization under Section 215 of the Federal Power Act. "Notice" has the meaning set forth in Section 11.1. "Percentage Interest" represents each Co-Tenant's undivided co-tenancy percentage ownership interest in the respective Shared Facilities (which corresponds to each Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity divided by the aggregate Maximum Capacity of all of the Co-Tenants) and is set forth on Exhibit D attached hereto with respect to each Co-Tenant, as such Exhibit D may be updated from time to time in accordance with this Agreement. "Permitted Liens" means: (a) Liens for taxes that (i) are not yet delinquent or (ii) are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings of which all the Parties have received written notice and for which adequate reserves have been established in accordance with GAAP, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any risk greater than a de minimis risk of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area (provided that in all events any such proceedings must be resolved and such Liens removed at least ninety (90) days before any such sale, forfeiture or loss event could occur); (b) Liens in favor of carriers, warehousemen, mechanics, materialmen, repairmen or other like Liens that (i) arise in the ordinary course of business of and for amounts that are not yet due or (ii) are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings of which all the Parties have received written notice and for which adequate reserves have been established in accordance with GAAP, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any risk greater than a de minimis risk of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area (provided that in all events any such proceedings must be resolved and such Liens removed at least ninety (90) days before any such sale, forfeiture or loss event could occur); (c) Liens in favor of Financing Parties permitted pursuant to Section 7.2(c); (d) Liens arising out of judgments or awards so long as enforcement has been stayed and for the payment of which adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP, bonds or other security reasonably acceptable to the applicable Co-Tenants have been provided or are fully covered by insurance; (e) minor defects, easements, licenses, rights-of-way, restrictions and other similar encumbrances incurred in the ordinary course of business, and encumbrances consisting of the zoning restrictions, licenses, restrictions on the use of property or minor imperfections in title, which do not impair the value of property affected thereby for the purpose for which title was acquired or interfere with the operation of any of the Projects; or (f) Liens incurred in the ordinary course of business in connection with surety and appeal bonds, performance bonds, worker's compensation, unemployment insurance, social security, other governmental rules and other obligations of a like nature to the extent the foregoing do not in the aggregate impair the use of the property or assets of any of the Co-Tenants or the value of such property or assets for the purposes of such business. "Person" means any individual, partnership, joint stock company, corporation, limited liability company, trust, unincorporated association or joint venture, any Governmental Authority, or any other entity. "Plan Comment Period" has the meaning set forth in Section 2.1(a). The Manager shall perform all services with respect to the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area as required under this Agreement through the date of termination or expiration of this Agreement or the removal or resignation of the Manager in accordance with this Article 3, and each Co-Tenant shall make all payments required by it hereunder through such date, with such payment to be made in full within thirty (30) days after such termination, expiration, removal or resignation. No resignation of the Manager in accordance with Section 3.3 shall be effective unless and until a successor Manager is appointed with the written approval of each Co-Tenant In the event of any removal or resignation of the Manager in accordance with this Article 3 or otherwise, the Manager shall provide reasonable assistance to the Co-Tenants to assure a smooth, efficient transition of its services to a replacement Manager, including in taking any necessary actions with respect to MISO, for which Manager shall be reimbursed its reasonable expenses in connection therewith. 3.5 Fixed Fee . As consideration for the management services to be performed by the Manager hereunder, beginning on the Effective Date and subject to this Article 3, the Manager shall be paid an annual fee equal to Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars ($25,000) (the "Fixed Fee"). The Fixed Fee shall be payable by the Operating Co-Tenants pro rata in accordance with their respective Share monthly in arrears at the rate of one-twelfth (1/12th) of the annual Fixed Fee, and may be prorated for partial months at the beginning and end of the term hereof. If any of the Operating Co-Tenants declare a Force Majeure Event, such Operating Co-Tenant shall continue to pay the Manager its Share of the Fixed Fee (as adjusted pursuant to this Section 3.5) and the reimbursable Shared Expenses in accordance with Section 3.5(b). The Fixed Fee and reimbursable Shared Expenses shall be allocated among, and paid by, WFS and each other Operating Co-Tenant to the extent pertaining to the period after each other Co-Tenant's Use Right Date, as a Shared Expense. (a) Fee Adjustments. The Fixed Fee shall be modified annually for each calendar year after the Effective Date by the percentage change in the GDPIPD, if increased, during such calendar year. (b) Reimbursement Expenses. In addition to the Fixed Fee (which shall fully compensate the Manager for its administrative services hereunder and the costs described in the last sentence of this Section 3.5(b)), the Manager shall be reimbursed for Shared Expenses pertaining to maintenance, repairs to and replacements of the Shared Facilities, and any other work performed by, or on behalf or, the Manager in carrying out its duties hereunder (subject to Section 3.9(d)), provided that, unless an Emergency has occurred (in which case, the provisions of Section 4.2 shall apply), the Manager shall not incur any unbudgeted expense without prior notice to, and receipt of approval from, the Operating Co-Tenants. The Manager shall be responsible, in connection with its performance hereunder, for (i) all payroll, withholding, social security, unemployment, accident insurance, health insurance, employee benefit, and other taxes of employees of the Manager, (ii) all taxes with respect to compensation paid to the Manager, including income and franchise taxes, (iii) all surcharges, penalties, fees and other governmental amounts and charges relating thereto, and such amounts shall not be reimbursable pursuant to this Section 3.5. (c) Untimely Payment. In the event an Operating Co-Tenant fails to make timely payment to the Manager of a properly rendered invoice for Shared Expenses in accordance with Section 2.7 of this Agreement to the extent pertaining to the time period when such Co-Tenant was an Operating Co-Tenant, then any such Operating Co-Tenant which fails to pay its respective allocated Share of such invoiced amount in accordance with this Agreement within twenty (20) days after receipt of a follow-up notice indicating that such Operating Co-Tenant shall be responsible for paying interest to a vendor or contractor if it fails to make such payment within 10 days after receipt of such notice, shall be severally responsible for any interest charged by a vendor or contractor as a result of the late payment of such invoice plus interest at the Interest Rate pursuant to Section 8.7. 3.6 Immunities . The Manager and its respective directors, officers, employees and agents shall not be liable to the Co-Tenants for any particular action taken, or decision not to take any action, if (i) such action was taken (or not taken) or decision was followed, as applicable, in accordance with the written approval or direction of the Co-Tenants and the Manager's standard of performance set forth in Section 4.11, or (ii) to the extent the Annual Shared Facilities Budget approved by the Operating Co-Tenants for such year does not provide the Manager with budget to perform such tasks. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Manager and its Representatives may consult with legal counsel, independent public accountants and other experts selected by it regarding the performance of its duties hereunder and shall not be liable for any action taken or omitted to be taken in good faith by it or them in accordance with the advice of such counsel, accountants or experts and the Manager's standard of performance in Section 4.11 to the extent the Manager reasonably believes such actions or omission to be within and consistent with the scope of the Manager's duties hereunder. 3.7 Non-Reliance . Each Co-Tenant represents, as of the Effective Date, that it has reviewed the terms of such documents and information that it has deemed appropriate, and that it has made its own appraisal in respect of the Shared Facilities, independently and without reliance on the Manager. Each Co-Tenant shall review the terms of such other documents and information that at the time it may deem appropriate, and it shall continue to make its own appraisal in respect of the Shared Facilities, or in respect of any matter for which such Co-Tenant may be entitled to vote or give consent under this Agreement, in any such case, independently and without reliance on the Manager. 3.8 Duties of the Manager. With respect to the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area, the Manager shall: (a) Represent the Co-Tenants in matters pertaining to any representations and warranties assigned to each Co-Tenant pertaining to the Shared Facilities, including (i) interaction with the warranty counterparties and monitoring each warrantor's performance of its obligations, (ii) coordinating and liaising with each warrantor, and (iii) enforcing the Co-Tenants' rights thereunder and actively participating and advocating on behalf of the Co-Tenants in any negotiations or disputes with each warrantor thereunder; (b) After the initial construction of the Shared Facilities is completed as provided in Section 2.1(a) above, the Manager shall be the primary party responsible for overseeing the maintenance, use and repair of the completed Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area and shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to maintain and manage the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area: (i) in good working order and repair in a reasonably expeditious and cost effective manner in accordance with the Annual Shared Facilities Budget, the Real Property Agreements and any applicable real property encumbrances, Applicable Law, Governmental Approvals, Prudent Industry Practice and this Agreement, and (ii) in accordance with the terms and provisions of each Co-Tenant's Power Purchase Agreement and Interconnection Agreement that specifically relate to the maintenance and management of the Shared Facilities (including terms and provisions that relate to limitations on, and scheduling of outages) but solely to the extent such maintenance and management terms and provisions are specifically detailed and described in a written notice delivered to the Manager by the Co-Tenant that is party to the applicable Interconnection Agreement and/or Power Purchase Agreement), in each case, Without Adverse Distinction Among the Co-Tenants; (c) If reasonably required in connection with maintenance and management of the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area and/or to permit the installation and testing of additions or modifications to the Shared Facilities and/or Project Specific Facilities installed by a Co-Tenant in the Shared Facilities Area as contemplated in Section 2.5(b) related to interconnecting its Project to the Shared Facilities, the Manager is authorized to temporarily interrupt service on the Shared Facilities, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement by and Without Adverse Distinction Among the Co-Tenants temporarily, by disconnecting all or any portions of the Projects and to require curtailments of the Shared Facilities in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice and in compliance with the terms of this Agreement; (d) provide to each Co-Tenant, upon request, any material documents concerning the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area required for a Co-Tenant to design, construct, operate, and maintain its Project in compliance with the Interconnection Agreements, Transmission Owner directives, Tariff, MPSC regulations, applicable NERC registration requirements and reliability standards, and Applicable Laws; (e) To the extent the Transmission Owner under the Interconnection Agreements requires a single point of contact for the matters described in this Section 3.8(e), act as such point of contact for each Co-Tenant in all required communications with the Transmission Owner pertaining to the operation of the Shared Facilities, maintain a record of all formal "Interconnection Request For Information" notifications, and forward any related communications to the applicable Co-Tenant, in relation to their respective Interconnection Agreements, promptly upon receipt or transmission of such communications; (f) procure or manage the procurement of insurance policies for the Shared Facilities pursuant to Article 6; (g) review and advise on all property tax requirements to be paid by WFS prior to the Election Date, and pay all property taxes on the Shared Facilities Area and Shared Facilities on and after the initial Election Date; (h) pay any property taxes assessed against the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area for which the Co-Tenants are responsible pursuant to the Real Property Agreements. All such taxes and assessments shall be treated as Shared Expenses; (i) pay and invoice for Shared Expenses due in connection with the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, and, from and after the Use Right Date, maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget; (j) coordinate with Co-Tenants regarding compliance with NERC standards with respect to their IFC design drawings for the Shared Facilities and interconnecting electrical, protection, and SCADA equipment; (k) upon the request of any Co-Tenant provide advice regarding plant testing and commissioning reports for compliance with safety and performance requirements; (l) in the event of a Loss Event with respect to the Shared Facilities, (i) lead and coordinate efforts to expedite the repair and/or replacement of the Shared Facilities and compile and distribute the requisite documentation for recovery of loss proceeds available to the Co-Tenants with respect to the All Risk Property Insurance referenced on Part B of Exhibit F, and (ii) as soon as reasonably practicable prepare a written proposal in consultation with the Co-Tenants to rebuild, repair, restore or replace the impacted Shared Facilities and determine the most appropriate response to such Loss Event in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice; (m) if requested by any Co-Tenant, review and advise such Co-Tenant on submissions to Governmental Authorities relating to NERC registration and the achievement of commercial operations; (n) notify each Co-Tenant in writing of (i) the assertion of any claim for property damage with in excess of fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) with respect to the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Area promptly following the Manager's knowledge of any such assertion and (ii) the Manager's knowledge of the occurrence of an event likely, in the reasonable determination of the Manager, to result in the assertion of such a claim promptly following any such occurrence; (o) maintain all WFS Project records that would be required for facilitating WFS2 Project interconnection and WFS3 Project interconnection during the construction and interconnection process, and providing any such records to WFS2 or WFS3, as applicable, upon receipt; (p) following the achievement of commercial operations of a Project, upon the request of the Co-Tenant owning such Project, review NERC testing or model updates for such Project; (q) take any and all action as may be reasonably necessary to enforce any joint Co-Tenant claims against third parties related to the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Area not involving the Manager or any of its Affiliates, including, without limitation warranty claims against the contractor that installs the Shared Facilities; provided shall not settle any such claims for claimed Liabilities in excess of $10,000 without the written approval by at least two (2) Co-Tenants which are not Affiliates representing a majority of the Percentage Interests; (r) take such other actions as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing to the extent consistent with the Annual Shared Facilities Budget or to address an Emergency, unless in any such case, such action is not in the commercially reasonable interest of the Co-Tenants. For the avoidance of doubt, the Manager shall pay all Shared Expenses in furtherance of the foregoing duties, and such Shared Expenses shall be reimbursed in accordance with Section 2.7. 3.9 Specific Authority of the Manager . Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Manager shall be responsible for the following actions without further approval from the Co-Tenants: (a) overseeing the operator under any Maintenance Services Agreement with respect to day-to-day management, operations and maintenance of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area in accordance with this Agreement; (b) performing the services set forth on Exhibit E, or overseeing the third party operator to whom responsibility for such matters has been subcontracted pursuant to a Maintenance Services Agreement, if applicable; (c) negotiating, entering into, executing, acknowledging or amending agreements relating to the management, use, maintenance, and repair of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget and any Maintenance Services Agreement and the other terms and provisions of this Agreement; provided, however, that (i) no such actions shall materially and adversely affect the rights or privileges of any Party under this Agreement or their use, operation, access to or availability of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area without the written consent of such Party, and (ii) the Manager shall provide each Co-Tenant with copies of any such agreement promptly upon execution thereof; (d) paying and collecting amounts due in connection with the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area in accordance with this Agreement, and maintaining one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Budget; and (e) executing, acknowledging, and delivering any and all instruments and taking such other steps as are reasonably necessary to carry out the duties of the Manager expressly provided herein and as are consistent therewith. 3.10 Reporting; Notices; Records . The Manager shall, from time to time, provide reports to the Co-Tenants sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area, including such matters related thereto as may have a material impact on the applicable Co-Tenant's Projects. The Manager's reporting obligations shall include all of the following: (a) provide data and information, to the extent requested by a Co-Tenant and to the extent in the Manager's possession or reasonably available to the Manager, regarding the Shared Facilities' performance and availability; (b) promptly provide the Co-Tenants written notice of any communications, orders or requirements of any Governmental Authority received by the Manager affecting the Shared Facilities and/or the Shared Facilities Area, in each case received by the Manager or of which the Manager has received written notice; (c) collect and provide any information, to the extent such information is in Manager's possession or reasonably available to Manager, regarding the Shared Facilities or the Shared Facilities Area required for any reports to, or filings with, any Governmental Authorities; (d) report promptly (and in any event within 24 hours of becoming aware thereof) to the Co-Tenants any incident of Emergency or Force Majeure Event of the Shared Facilities or the Shared Facilities Area or otherwise adversely affecting any of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, of which the Manager becomes aware; and (e) Cooperate fully and provide such records and other information that may be reasonably requested by any of the Co-Tenants in connection with (i) the filing of its tax returns, (ii) the maintenance and retention of its books and records, (iii) any financial reporting or other disclosures that may be required, and (iv) any audit, litigation or other proceeding by any Governmental Authority, including those that pertain to taxes. 3.11 Audit Rights . The Manager shall allow the Co-Tenants and the Co-Tenants' authorized Representatives to inspect and audit the books and records maintained by the Manager with respect to the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area (at the Co-Tenants' sole cost and expense); provided, however, that each of the Co-Tenants shall, at its own expense, only have the right to inspect and audit such books and records for any period that is within five (5) years from the date of an applicable payment is made hereunder or the final settlement or disposition of any claim made pursuant to this Agreement. If any such inspection or audit discloses an error and that, as a result thereof, any overpayment or any underpayment has occurred hereunder, the amount thereof shall be paid within thirty (30) days after receipt of an invoice (with reasonable supporting detail) with interest at the Interest Rate (except that any underpayment caused by the actions or inactions of Manager will not bear interest) to the Co-Tenant to whom it is owed by the Manager or other Co-Tenants obligated therefor, as applicable; provided, further, that a Co-Tenant shall only be liable for any amounts hereunder that relate to errors discovered and disclosed within the inspection and audit period provided for in this provision. ARTICLE 4 OTHER DUTIES OF THE MANAGER 4.1 Budget/Maintenance Services Agreement. (a) On or before September 30th of each year, the Manager shall provide each Operating Co-Tenant (and each Co-Tenant which has delivered an Election Notice (an "Election Notice Co-Tenant")) with a proposed budget for maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area to be used for the following calendar year (an "Annual Shared Facilities Budget"), describing the scheduled work to be completed in the following calendar year and the general operational plans for the Shared Facilities during such year, including responsibilities and emergency procedures and detailing the expected expenses for the following calendar year including explanations for any material differences from the prior calendar year and such draft budget shall include, at a minimum, the billing rates, estimated cost, based on time and materials, and all fees and reimbursable costs contemplated in this Agreement, for anticipated maintenance services and repairs to be provided by or contracted for by the Manager during each month of the following year (or portions thereof). Each Operating Co-Tenant and each Election Notice Co-Tenant may submit any comments or questions to the Manager within thirty (30) days of receipt of the draft Annual Shared Facilities Budget. The Manager shall incorporate any comments received and shall provide a proposed final Annual Shared Facilities Budget to the Operating Co-Tenants and Election Notice Co-Tenants by November 30th of each year for approval by each Operating Co-Tenant and Election Notice Co-Tenant. In the event that a proposed Annual Shared Facilities Budget is not approved in accordance with the foregoing requirements by January 1 of any year, (i) the Annual Shared Facilities Budget prepared and approved for the previous year shall be utilized until such time as a new Annual Shared Facilities Budget is approved by the Operating Co-Tenants and Election Notice Co-Tenants pursuant to the process above or an alternative or modified Annual Shared Facilities Budget is determined pursuant to the Dispute resolution process set forth in Article 9; and (ii) each Operating Co-Tenant and Election Notice Co-Tenant shall have the right to submit for resolution pursuant to Article 9 any Dispute regarding the appropriateness and/or reasonableness of any amounts or items proposed to be included in any proposed Annual Shared Facilities Budget for a calendar year. The Annual Shared Facilities Budget may be amended during the year with the written consent of each Co-Tenant. (b) If, during any calendar year the Manager believes that a variance (in excess of the permitted variances described in Section 4.1(c) below) is reasonably likely to occur between the actual expense of operating and maintaining the Shared Facilities and the budgeted expense for a particular material budget item as provided in the then-applicable Annual Shared Facilities Budget, the Manager shall timely notify the Operating Co-Tenants and any Election Notice Co-Tenants of such belief in writing and advise such Co-Tenants of the necessary revisions to the Annual Shared Facilities Budget and the reasons for those revisions. If the Operating Co-Tenants and Election Notice Co-Tenants approve, such Co-Tenants and the Manager shall proceed in good faith to revise the Annual Shared Facilities Budget in such manner for the balance of the year. (c) Commercially reasonable and necessary costs and expenses actually incurred by the Manager that are within ten percent (10%) of any line item on the Annual Shared Facilities Budget and do not in the aggregate cause the overall Annual Shared Facilities Budget to be exceeded, and which are otherwise incurred in accordance with the most recently Annual Shared Facilities Budget, shall not require any additional approval of the Operating Co-Tenants. (d) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, the Manager shall not be required to take any action that would cause it to incur expenses in excess of the Annual Shared Facilities Budget, as it may be amended pursuant to Section 4.1(b), except in cases of Emergency. 4.2 Emergency Actions. In the event of any Emergency involving the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, the Manager shall take such action as may be reasonable and necessary to prevent, avoid or mitigate injury, loss of life, or damage or destruction of property and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such Emergency, including the Manager's response thereto, to the Parties. 4.3 Limitation on Authority. The Manager shall not, without the approval of all of the Co-Tenants take any actions hereunder or with respect to the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Area which would be inconsistent with or outside the scope of the express duties and authority of the Manager set forth herein, including, without limitation the following: (a) create, permit or cause to be created any Lien through or under Manager (other than Permitted Liens excluding Liens in favor of Financing Parties) on any of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area (b) invoice the Operating Co-Tenants for any Shared Expenses resulting from work or services performed or equipment supplied by an Affiliate of the Manager except pursuant to arrangements on terms which are reasonably consistent with "arms-length" terms including pricing which is reasonably consistent with "fair market" pricing; (c) perform or omit to perform any act that would cause any Person to reasonably believe that the Manager is a partner of the Co-Tenants or authorized to bind such Co-Tenants, except as expressly authorized herein; (d) transfer all or any portion of the Undivided Interests held by any Co-Tenant, or any components of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area (other than pursuant to this Agreement); (e) borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of a Co-Tenant; or (f) take any action intended to prevent or obstruct any non-defaulting Co-Tenant from using the Shared Facilities to transmit electricity from its Project to the Point of Interconnection in an amount up to its/their Maximum Capacity, in each case, other than as may be expressly permitted pursuant to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. 4.4 Manager Activities . The Manager shall not, without the approval of the Parties, take any action that would prevent the development, construction or operation of, otherwise result in a material impairment of, a Co-Tenant's Project or the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area, unless required to do so by Applicable Law, in an Emergency, or by Prudent Industry Practice. If the Manager intends to conduct (or cause to be conducted) any material maintenance and/or repair work on the Shared Facilities which could potentially require any Co-Tenant to temporarily interrupt, reduce or curtail deliveries of energy from its Project to or on the Shared Facilities, then the Manager shall (i) except in the event of an Emergency, provide at least thirty (30) days prior written notice to the potentially impacted Co-Tenant(s) of the contemplated commencement of such work, and (ii) use its good faith efforts to conduct such activities so as to minimize, to the extent reasonably possible, interference with the Co-Tenants use of the Shared Facilities and their Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area. The Manager shall (and shall cause any of its contractors or subcontractors to) conduct any maintenance and repair work to the Shared Facilities and/or in the Shared Facilities Area in compliance with the Real Property Agreements, Applicable Law and Governmental Approvals applicable to such work and Prudent Industry Practice. The Manager shall not be required to provide prior written notice to conduct work as reasonably required to address an Emergency, but the Manager shall provide notice of such work to the Co-Tenants as soon as reasonably practicable. 4.5 Cooperation with MISO, MPSC and the Transmission Owner . Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, the Manager shall cooperate with MISO, MPSC and the Transmission Owner (and any successor agency or other entities having authority over the Shared Facilities) to make all such information, reports, logs and other documents relating to the Shared Facilities available to MISO, MPSC and the Transmission Owner as may be required pursuant to the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreements (or other agreements providing interconnection service to the Projects), and to support the completion of any required interconnection studies, and Applicable Law. 4.6 Cooperation with Financing Parties . Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, the Manager shall during normal business hours and upon reasonable prior notice, cooperate with the Parties' Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants and shall make all information, reports, logs and other documents relating to the Shared Facilities available to such Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants, and shall make the Manager's personnel available for consultation with such Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants all as reasonably requested. The Manager also agrees that it shall, at any time and from time to time during the Term of this Agreement, after receipt of a written request from a Party, execute and deliver to such Party and its Financing Parties any consents to collateral assignments or estoppel certificates as may reasonably be requested, with the requesting Party to promptly reimburse the Manager for any documented reasonable out of pocket legal or other costs incurred by the Manager in connection with the execution and delivery thereof. 4.7 Scope of Manager Duties and Authority . The Manager shall have no authority or obligations or liability for any obligations except those expressly stated in this Agreement, and nothing in this Agreement shall obligate the Manager to perform any duties or assume any liabilities under any agreement to which the Manager is not directly a party unless such duties are also expressly stated in this Agreement and then only to such extent. The Co-Tenants acknowledge that the Manager's performance under this Agreement is dependent upon the Manager (a) having reasonable access to the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area, (b) receipt of required approvals and consents on a timely basis from the Co-Tenants, where applicable, and (c) promptly receiving all applicable reimbursements when due and payable hereunder in full on a timely basis from the Operating Co-Tenants. 4.8 Inspection by Co-Tenants . The Manager shall permit the Co-Tenants to inspect the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area during regular business hours; provided that the applicable Co-Tenant arranges in advance of any such inspection with Manager and complies with the reasonable safety requirements imposed by Manager. 4.9 Risk of Loss; Loss Events. (a) Risk of Loss. Subject to the provisions of Article 10, in the event of a Loss Event, if the proceeds of the All Risk Insurance and/or any condemnation proceeds, as applicable, do not cover the full cost of rebuilding and restoring the Shared Facilities, each Co-Tenant shall contribute a portion equal to its Percentage Interest of the total amount by which the cost of rebuilding and restoring the Shared Facilities exceeds the amount of insurance proceeds available from the All Risk Insurance (or other insurance) or condemnation proceeds available for such purpose (any such excess cost amount is referred to the "Co-Tenants' Loss Event Contribution Amount"). (b) Loss Events. Upon the occurrence of a Loss Event, the Manager or any Co-Tenant receiving notice shall provide the other Parties with reasonable advance notice of any impending proceeding or meeting related to such Loss Event and shall not in the absence of the consent of all Co-Tenants settle with any other party in respect thereof or agree on compensation for such Loss Event. The Manager shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, prepare a written proposal (a "Restoration Proposal") in consultation with the Co-Tenants to rebuild, repair, restore or replace the portion of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area affected by such Loss Event as expeditiously and cost effectively as reasonably possible consistent with Prudent Industry Practice, which Restoration Proposal shall contain, in appropriate detail, (i) a budget identifying all categories and approximate amounts reasonably anticipated to be incurred, (ii) a progress and completion schedule and (iii) a written plan, in each case, for the proposed rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the Shared Facilities and/or Shared Facilities Area. The Manager, to the extent necessary or prudent, may coordinate preparation of the Restoration Proposal with similar activity undertaken by or on behalf of any of the Co-Tenants arising out of the Loss Event in respect of Project Specific Facilities. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the preparation of the Restoration Proposal shall be Shared Expenses reimbursed by each Co-Tenant in proportion to its Percentage Interest as of the date of the Loss Event. Within twenty (20) days after receipt of a Restoration Proposal from the Manager, each Co-Tenant shall notify the Manager and each other Co-Tenant in writing of any comments or concerns pertaining to the Restoration Proposal. The Manager shall consider any comments or concerns delivered by the Co-Tenants within such twenty (20) day time period in good faith and deliver a final Restoration Proposal as quickly as reasonably possible thereafter (but in all event within 10 days). Any comments or concerns of a Co-Tenant not addressed to a Co-Tenant's reasonable satisfaction in the final Restoration Proposal may be resolved as a Dispute pursuant to Article 9; provided (i) the Manager shall be authorized to proceed with the restoration work in accordance with the Restoration Proposal, and (ii) each Co-Tenant shall be obligated to contribute a portion equal to its Percentage Interest of any Co-Tenants' Loss Event Contribution Amount required to complete the work in the Restoration Proposal, unless and until a court (pursuant to an injunction or like order) or the arbitrator determines otherwise. (c) Any award or other compensation payable to the Co-Tenants to the extent pertaining to the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Area as a consequence of any Condemnation Event shall be first applied to pay the cost of restoring or rebuilding the Shared Facilities, and any excess left thereafter shall be paid to each Co-Tenant in proportion to each Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. 4.10 Manager Representative . The Manager may, by written notice to the Co-Tenants, designate an individual representative of the Manager (the "Manager Representative") whose instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon the Manager in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Manager Representative shall not have the authority to (a) amend or terminate, or waive any right of the Manager under, this Agreement or (b) initiate any litigation or commence any formal dispute. The Manager shall have the right to change the Manager Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the Co-Tenants. 4.11 Standards of Performance . Throughout the Term of this Agreement, the Manager shall perform the services and all other obligations of the Manager under this Agreement in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices, the Annual Shared Facilities Budget, the Interconnection Agreements, the Real Property Agreements, the Tariff (including all applicable technical and operational rules and limitations), and all Applicable Laws and Governmental Approvals and the other terms and provisions of this Agreement, including, without limitation, those set forth in Section 3.8(b). 4.12 Assignment of Warranties . The Manager shall be responsible for enforcing, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, all manufacturer, construction and other warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities and any parts or materials associated therewith. The Co-Tenants and the Manager shall cooperate in the enforcement of the foregoing warranties, and to the extent possible, any Co-Tenant that is not also the Manager holding a warranty for a portion of the Shared Facilities shall assign such warranty to Manager for enforcement and collection, and any funds received in lieu of repair or replacement shall be used for the repair or replacement of the affected Shared Facilities. Any excess warranty funds shall be distributed to the Co-Tenants in proportion to their Percentage Interest in such Shared Facilities. The Manager's documented out of pocket costs and expenses incurred in enforcing said warranties shall be included in the Shared Expenses hereunder. 4.13 Step-in Rights . In addition to any other rights or remedies a Co-Tenant may have, in the case of a Manager Event of Default, any Co-Tenant unaffiliated with the Manager shall have the right to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform on behalf of the Manager after the expiration of the relevant cure period (or to cause a third party to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform such task).
ARTICLE 5 COVENANTS 5.1 Covenants of Co-Tenants . (a) Standards of Performance. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, each Co-Tenant will conduct its activities and operations with respect to the use of the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area, and perform its obligations under this Agreement, in each case in accordance with (a) all Applicable Laws, (b) Prudent Industry Practices, (c) the terms of its respective Interconnection Agreement and the Real Property Agreements, (d) the Tariff (including all applicable technical and operational rules and limitations), (e) any and all Governmental Approvals and (f) this Agreement. Except as provided herein, no Co-Tenant will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement, its respective Interconnection Agreement, the Real Property Agreements or any Governmental Approvals applicable to such Co-Tenant or the Shared Facilities in a manner that adversely affects the other Co-Tenants or another Co-Tenant Project or gives rise to a Liability affecting the other Co-Tenants, another Co-Tenant Project, the Shared Facilities or the Shared Facilities Area, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that imposes costs on or results in damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of another Co-Tenant Projects unless required to do so by Applicable Law. (b) Improvements in Shared Facilities Area. No Party shall install any improvements in the Shared Facilities Area other than (i) Shared Facilities and any Project Specific Facilities installed in accordance with Sections 2.1 and 2.5, related to interconnecting its Project using the Shared Facilities up to its Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection, and (ii) such other improvements which may be installed to comply with Applicable Law, Governmental Approvals and the Real Property Agreements, to respond to an Emergency or which may be approved by the Parties. Subject to the terms and provisions of this Agreement and the Real Property Agreements, each Co-Tenant shall have the right to operate, access and utilize its Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area in accordance with this Agreement and except as expressly permitted pursuant to this Agreement or the Real Property Agreements, no other Co-Tenant shall interfere therewith. (c) Regulatory Status. (i) No Co-Tenant shall take any action that could reasonably be expected to adversely impact the other Co-Tenant's ability to qualify as an EWG. (ii) No Co-Tenant shall use the Shared Facilities (A) to provide "retail electric utility service" as that phrase is used in Miss. Code Ann. Section 77-3-3(d)(i); or (B) in a manner that would cause any Co-Tenant to be considered an "electric utility" or a "transmission and distribution utility" as that term is defined in Miss. Code Ann. Section 77-3-3(d)(i). (iii) Prior to generating any electricity from its respective Project, each Co-Tenant shall, if required pursuant to the MISO participant requirements applicable to such Co-Tenant, execute and comply with MISO's Market Participant Agreement. (iv) Each Co-Tenant shall use the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area only for the purpose of transmitting electricity generated from its Project (or to carry backfeed power) and in such a way as to preserve the non-"electric utility" status of such Co-Tenant as that term is defined in Miss. Code Ann. Section 77-3-3(d)(i). No Co-Tenant shall use the Shared Facilities to transmit an amount of electrical energy greater than its Maximum Capacity. Each Co-Tenant shall, subject to any requirements of Applicable Law, avoid taking any action that would cause the Shared Facilities to be subject to any open access rights or to be regulated as a public Transmission Owner. (v) No Co-Tenant shall (A) provide any interconnection or transmission services to any other Co-Tenant under this Agreement, or, except as may be required by Applicable Law, have any obligation to another Co-Tenant to provide any interconnection or related rights with a transmission provider, or (B) pay a fee or make any other payment to another Co-Tenant for the transmission of the other Co-Tenant's electricity. (d) Taxes. Unless otherwise directed by the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall pay all taxes levied against the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area for which the Co-Tenants are responsible under the terms of the Real Property Agreements before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty will become due or be imposed for their non-payment, except that the Manager may withhold payment of any tax if the Manager is contesting the payment of such taxes at the direction of the Co-Tenants by appropriate proceedings and such proceeding does not involve any danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of such Shared Facilities or any Shared Facilities Area, including the posting of any bond that is required by Applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while the payment of such tax is being contested and notifies all of the Co-Tenants thereof in writing at least thirty (30) days before such payment is due or paid. All such taxes and assessments paid by the Manager shall be treated as Shared Expenses and invoiced to the Co-Tenants in accordance with Section 2.7. Each Co-Tenant acknowledges that it shall be liable for its own taxes with respect to any of its Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area or otherwise. (e) Environmental Compliance. Each Co-Tenant shall, with respect to its Project, (including its Project Specific Facilities, including the Project Site upon which its Project is installed), be responsible for and shall have exclusive control over all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by (i) any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters, or (ii) any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such Co-Tenant's use, operation or ownership of its Project (including its Project Specific Facilities and Project Site). The Manager shall, with respect to the Shared Facilities, oversee under the direction of the Co-Tenants all investigations, studies, clean-up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Co-Tenant's use operation or ownership of the Shared Facilities, and each Party shall be responsible as provided in Article 10 for all Liabilities related to investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action and any violations of, or noncompliance with, Environmental Laws caused by such Party or its Representatives. The Manager shall keep all Co-Tenants fully apprised as to the above matters and shall consult with all of them prior to taking any action involving any Governmental Authority or risk of incurring any Liability, and the Co-Tenants shall manage and control all investigations and any environmental clean-up, remediation or related activities with respect to such Shared Facilities, or direct Manager to do so. (f) Interconnection. A Co-Tenant may take such actions as may be necessary to comply with any order received from the Transmission Owner, the MPSC, MISO or any successor balancing authority responsible for the reliability of the Transmission Owner's system at the Point of Interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreements, and nothing herein shall require a Co-Tenant to violate the requirements of any such order. If any Co-Tenant amends it's Interconnection Agreement, it shall promptly provide a copy of such amendment to the other Parties. This Agreement does not grant any Party any rights to interconnection service or other rights under any Interconnection Agreement to any Person that is not a party to such Interconnection Agreement. (g) Voting or Approval Rights. Prior to the first Use Right Date, WFS alone shall have the right to approve the Annual Shared Facilities Budget and Maintenance Services Agreement and any amendments thereto. On and after the first Use Right Date, each Operating Co-Tenant shall have the right to vote or give its approval, on any matter requiring or needing a vote or approval of the Co-Tenants. On and after the first Use Right Date, unless otherwise specified herein, the unanimous approval of the Co-Tenants shall be required for any matters which require the vote or approval of the Co-Tenants (other than Major Decisions or as otherwise expressly provided herein). Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, any Major Decision shall require the unanimous approval of the Co-Tenants. (h) No Dedication of Property; No Public Access. Each Party agrees that entering into this Agreement, performing its obligations hereunder, or exercising its rights hereunder, either in whole or part, is not intended to be, and shall in no way be construed as or deemed to be a dedication to public or quasi-public use or purpose of any of the Project Specific Facilities of any Party, any Shared Facilities or the Shared Facilities Area, or any portion of the foregoing. The Co-Tenants undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting physical access to the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area, including permitting the Manager to establish and enforce reasonable procedures and protocol for security, safety, and protection of the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties shall comply with requirements set forth in any Governmental Approvals. (i) Co-Location Rights. Each Co-Tenant hereunder shall be permitted to construct its Project Specific Facilities on the Shared Facilities Area subject to the terms and provisions of this Agreement, in each case solely to the extent necessary to interconnect its Project up to its Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. Each Co-Tenant shall conduct its activities and operations with respect to the use of the Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area in accordance with this Agreement, Prudent Industry Practice, Applicable Law, the Real Estate Agreements and any applicable Governmental Approvals. The Parties shall cooperate in good faith to (i) jointly manage, utilize and maintain the completed Shared Facilities (and the Governmental Approvals and Shared Facilities Area related thereto) to facilitate the shared use thereof by the Co-Tenants for the purposes of this Agreement, and (ii) to allow each Co-Tenant to interconnect its respective Project, and to permit each Co-Tenant to install any Project Specific Facilities and modifications to the Shared Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area required to interconnect such Co-Tenant's Project up to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection; provided any such installation shall be completed in accordance with this Agreement, including, without limitation Section 2.5 above. In furtherance of the Co-Tenants' agreements set forth in this paragraph, the Co-Tenants have agreed that without the prior written consent of other Co-Tenants, no Co-Tenant shall amend any Governmental Approval or Real Property Agreement in a manner which could reasonably be expected to adversely impact, or take any action not expressly permitted pursuant to this Agreement to intentionally interfere with, the other Co-Tenant's ability to install, maintain, operate and repair the Shared Facilities or their Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area which are required to interconnect their respective Projects utilizing the Shared Facilities and their Project Specific Facilities in the Shared Facilities Area, in each case as contemplated by this Agreement. (j) Co-Tenants' Responsibilities to Manager. Each Co-Tenant shall do all of the following: (i) with the exception of information and data the Manager is required to record and collect hereunder, provide the Manager with all material information requested by the Manager, including information related to permits, agreements, data and documents for the Shared Facilities in each case solely to the extent reasonably required for Manager to perform its obligations under this Agreement; (ii) promptly examine all material documents submitted by Manager and render any necessary decisions pertaining thereto; (iii) promptly make decisions required under this Agreement or any other agreement that the Manager may be requested to administer hereunder and respond to all reasonable requests from Manager for approval made hereunder; (iv) promptly execute and deliver such evidence of Manager's authority hereunder as may be reasonably required by third parties; and (v) except where the same are being disputed in good faith, pay by the due date set forth in this Agreement (A) payments of its Share of Shared Expenses to the extent consistent with then applicable Annual Shared Facilities Budget and incurred in accordance with Manager's authority hereunder and (B) any other payments required to be made by such Co-Tenant in connection with the Shared Facilities and/or the Shared Facilities Area pursuant to the express terms of this Agreement. (f) Subject to the terms of this Section 6.1(f) and the requirements of Applicable Law, so long as a Party is not in default under the terms of this Agreement, such Party shall have the right to self-insure the risks that would otherwise be covered by the commercial general liability and other insurance on Part A of Exhibit F required to be maintained by a Party by the terms of Sections 6.1(a) through (c) above. ARTICLE 7 TRANSFER OF INTERESTS; LIENS 7.1 Assignment Rights. (a) Except as otherwise permitted herein, no Party may Transfer its rights or obligations under this Agreement or its Undivided Interest or Maximum Capacity rights without the prior written consent of each other Co-Tenant, which consent may not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. This Agreement will be binding on, and inure to the benefit of, the Parties and their successors and permitted assigns. (a) Transfer by a Co-Tenant. Except as set forth in Section 7.2(c), no Co-Tenant may Transfer its rights in its Undivided Interest or Maximum Capacity rights or any of its rights or interests under this Agreement without obtaining the prior written consent of the other Co-Tenants, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, or delayed. Any Transfer of a Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest, Maximum Capacity rights or any other rights and interests in this Agreement (other than a mere collateral assignment to a Financing Party) shall require that, as of the effective date of such Transfer, (i) the transferee agrees in writing to bound by all the terms and conditions of this Agreement in the place and stead of the transferring Co-Tenant with respect to the portion of its rights and interests so transferred, including any obligation of the transferring Co-Tenant under this Agreement accruing or arising after the effective date of such Transfer, and (ii) all required Governmental Approvals have been obtained (if and to the extent necessary). (b) Transfer by Manager. Except as set forth in Section 7.2(c), Manager may not Transfer all or any part of its rights or interests under this Agreement (i) without the prior written consent of each Co-Tenant (such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, or delayed), and (ii) unless the applicable transferee has assumed, in writing, all of the duties and obligations of the Manager under this Agreement, including any obligation of transferring Manager under this Agreement accruing or arising after the effective date of such Transfer. (a) Prior to their respective Use Right Dates, each of WFS2 and WFS3 shall at its election and sole discretion have the right to withdraw from this Agreement without liability, subject to any obligations of WFS2 and WFS3 which expressly survive such termination pursuant to the terms of this Agreement. (ii) To the establishment of any reserves that the Manager deems reasonably necessary for any contingent or unforeseen liabilities or obligations or debts not yet payable by the Co-Tenants in connection with the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area, including any reserves to pay costs associated with the decommissioning and removal of the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area. ARTICLE 8 DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 8.1 Demand for Payment or Performance. NOW THEREFORE, the Parties hereby provide notice that they have agreed as follows: 1. Use of Shared Facilities and Shared Facilities Area. Subject to the terms and conditions of the Agreement, applicable Governmental Approvals and each Co-Tenant's Interconnection Agreement, once the initial installation of the Shared Facilities are completed, WFS and each other Operating Co-Tenant (as of its Use Right Date) shall have the right to utilize the Shared Facilities and the Shared Facilities Area (together with its Project Specific Facilities) to interconnect its Project(s) at 230kV and to deliver electrical energy generated by its Project(s) up to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. Total line losses will be allocated among the Projects as follows:

IA = average per-phase current (in amperes) of resource A IB = average per-phase current (in amperes) of resource B IC = average per-phase current (in amperes) of resource C RT = per-phase resistance (in ohms) of the common transmission line to the MISO POI ITOTAL = Total current from all resources (IA + IB + IC) (in amperes) TKW LOSS = Total Calculated Line Loss (in kW)
